Personal Loan Campaing¶

Introduction¶

AllLife US Bank has loan department that is looking to grow their customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. Borrowers (asset customers) is quite small. AllLife US Bank is looking to expand asset customers to bring in more loan business and earn more through interest on loans. Management is interested in more ways of converting liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

Objective¶

As Data Scientists for AllLife Bank we will build an accurate model to help the marketing department, identify potential customers (new and current customers) who have higher probability of purchasing a loan.

Key Questions¶

  1. To predict whether a liability customer will buy a personal loan or not.
  2. Which variables are most significant.
  3. Which segment of customers should be targeted more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank?
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities?
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)?

def perc_on_bar(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

## Function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set(palette='nipy_spectral')
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x,copy_df['Personal_Loan'],margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print('-'*120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(x,copy_df['Personal_Loan'],normalize='index')
    tab.plot(kind='bar',stacked=True,figsize=(10,5))
    plt.show()

Linear Regression¶

The Chi-Square test is a statistical method to determine if two categorical variables have a significant correlation between them.

Null Hypothesis - There is no association between the two variables. Alternate Hypothesis - There is an association between two variables.

In [68]:
import scipy.stats as stats
crosstab = pd.crosstab(copy_df['Personal_Loan'],copy_df['Online'])  # Contingency table of region and smoker attributes

Ho = "Online has no effect on personal loan"   # Stating the Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Online has an effect on personal loan"   # Stating the Alternate Hypothesis

chi, p_value, dof, expected =  stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) > 0.05')

Online has no effect on personal loan as the p_value (0.569) > 0.05

Ha = "Education_3 has an effect on personal loan"   # Stating the Alternate Hypothesis

chi, p_value, dof, expected =  stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) > 0.05')

Education_3 has an effect on personal loan as the p_value (0.0) < 0.05

## Function to create confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[0, 1]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(xtest)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

##  Function to calculate recall score
def get_recall_score(model):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    pred_train = model.predict(xtrain)
    pred_test = model.predict(xtest)
    print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(ytrain,pred_train))
    print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(ytest,pred_test))

# Choose the type of classifier. 
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(1,10), 
              'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5, 7, 10,15,20],
              'max_leaf_nodes' : [5, 10,15,20,25,30],
              'min_impurity_decrease': [0.0001,0.001,0.01,0.1]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(xtrain, ytrain)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
estimator.fit(xtrain, ytrain)

Business Insights¶

  • Income, Education_3 (Advanced/Professional), Education_2 (Graduate Degree) are the 3 most important variables when determining if a customer will get a personal loan
  • 291 customers that have a personal loan go online for bank services
  • 142 customers that have a personal loan have a credit card
  • 204 customers that have an advanced/professional education have personal loans
  • 180 customers that have a graduate degree have a personal loan
  • 133 customers that have more family size of 4 have personal loans. More than family sizes of 1,2,3
  • 240 customers that live in South California have personal loans
  • customers between 0-41 years of experience working have personal loans

Recommendations¶

  • 2673 customers dont have a personal loan and go online for bank services
  • 1316 customers dont have a personal loan but have credit cards
  • 1210 customers dont have a personal loan but have a graduate degree
  • 1287 customers dont have a personal loan but have advanced/professional education
  • 1183 customers dont have a personal loan but have family size of 2
  • 870 customers dont have a personal loan but have family size of 3
  • 1082 customers dont have a personal loan but have a family size of 4
  • 2259 customers dont have a personal loan but live in South California
  • Target customers that have a high income of '$'70K-'$'350K with announcements and promotions while customers are navigating the online services.
  • Target customers with big family sizes of 3
  • Target customers with high credit card average spending per month
  • Target customers with graduate degrees, advanced, professional education. They are more prone to get a personal loan.
